                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d942">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">867.00/3129: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Thurston</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-03-24T20:00:00+03:00"
                            >March 24, 1942—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received March 24—6:32 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>85. Vice Commissar Dekanosov inquired of me this evening whether the Soviet
                    Government might advise the Turkish Government that the American Government had
                    supplied the information regarding the German origin of the attempt on Von Papen
                    which I recently conveyed to Vyshinski.</p>
                <p>I replied that although I had no doubt that the information was furnished in
                    order that it might be employed as the Soviet Government saw fit, I would have
                    to request instructions with respect to its attribution to my Government.</p>
                <p>Prompt instructions are requested.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Thurston</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
